deck_excerpt: It's a great deck for beginners!
deck_description:
Swordsoul is a powerful archetype whose core cards can be obtained by completing the Rookie and Returner Mutual Follower Campaign! Completing the campaign twice will give you two Sword of Souls Structure Decks plus Swordsoul Sinister Sovereign - Qixing Longyuan as a bonus; what a great start! Mastering this deck will teach you the basics of modern Yu-Gi-Oh!

Staples to craft

x1 Baronne de Fleur

This amazing monster can negate and destroy almost any card, destroy another card on the field for free, and shuffle herself back into the deck to revive a monster in your graveyard. She's very easy to summon with Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan + a Swordsoul token.

x3 Maxx "C"

A staple for nearly every deck, it gives you free draws whenever your opponent special summons!

x2 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring

It's a blank check for most decks that could also negate Maxx C before it becomes a problem. You can buy 1 free Ash Blossom using gems at the shop and the rest can be crafted.

x2 Called by the Grave

This is a flexible card that not only negates hand traps like Ash Blossom and Maxx C, but also disrupts the opponent's graveyard strategies.

x1 Crossout Designator

This card is great for negating the effect of a card both you and your opponent are likely to have.

x3 Infinite Impermanence

Good when going first and second, this card can negate spell, trap, monster effects depending on whether it was set before activating. Be careful of the columns hit by Infinite Impermanence!

x1 Archnemeses Protos

This intimidating card is easy to summon, cannot be destroyed by a card effect, is searchable with Swordsoul Emergence, and has a devastating effect that destroys and restricts the attributes of monsters both players can special summon. It cannot destroy itself by its own effect, so you can use it to lock out dark monsters for free!

x2 Baxia, Brightness of the Yang Zing

It's another flexible card whose effects can be used multiple times in a turn. The first effect is great for dismantling boards. The second effect can destroy a card you control to revive a monster like Swordsoul of Taia or Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous from your graveyard to extend your plays.

x1 Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing

It can clear boards like Baxia but through destruction. It can destroy itself and 1 card your opponent controls. If it is destroyed, then you can special summon a wyrm like Swordsoul of Mo Ye or Taia from the deck to extend your plays. You can synchro summon Yazi by changing your wyrm monster's level with Swordsoul Emergence's banish effect.

Optional Cards

Psychic End Punisher

It's nearly unstoppable when you're low on life points. Incredible Ecclesia + Tenyi Spirit - Vishuda or Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna or Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring + a level 8 synchro can summon it.

Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing

You can summon Chaofeng in an advanced combo involving Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna + Swordsoul of Taia + Vishuda or Tenyi Spirit - Adhara; more on this later. In short, it can create a combo line that prevents your opponent from activating the effects of light monsters like Nibiru, the Primal Being, Centur-Ion Primera, or Lo, the Prayers of the Voiceless Voice.

Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit

She is a general purpose hand trap that can destroy annoying cards like Nightmare Pain and S:P Little Knight. Triple Tactics Talent is a good alternative to this card.

Pot of Desires

It allows you to draw 2 cards and power up Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying to new heights.

Draco Berserker of the Tenyi

He's a level 8 synchro wyrm that requires generic materials to summon and has great effects. He can be summoned under your Ashuna's and the opponent's Clockwork Night type locks!

The Nibiru-Resistant Chaofeng Combo Example

Requires Swordsoul of Taia + Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna + Tenyi Spirit - Adhara or Tenyi Spirit - Vishuda in your hand. This combo example will assume you have Vishuda in the hand, so Adhara would later be special summoned from the deck. You can use this combo to protect your Swordsoul plays from Nibiru, the Primal Being with minimal investment.

1. Activate Ashuna's effect to special summon itself from the hand.

2. Use Ashuna as link material for Monk of the Tenyi.

3. Activate Vishuda's effect to special summon itself from the hand.

4. Activate Ashuna's graveyard effect to special summon Adhara from the deck. This will lock you into special summoning only wyrms for the rest of the turn.

5. Synchro summon Baxia, Brightness of the Yang Zing by using Vishuda and Adhara as material. The opponent must Nibiru here or on step 6, or its effect won't activate.

6. Activate Baxia's effect to revive Adhara from the graveyard by destroying Monk of the Tenyi.

7. Synchro summon Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing by using Baxia and Adhara as material. Now the opponent can't activate light monster effects, and you can start your Swordsoul plays.

8. Normal summon Swordsoul of Taia.

9. Activate Taia's effect to summon a token by banishing Monk of the Tenyi from your graveyard.

10. Activate Adhara's graveyard effect to add Ashuna from the banish zone back to your hand.

11. Synchro summon Swordsoul Grandmaster - Chixiao by using Taia and the token as material.

12. Activate Chixiao's effect as chain link 1 and Taia's effect as chain link 2. You can send any wyrm to the graveyard and search for any Swordsoul card you'd like.

Any wyrm you send to the graveyard can be banished with Swordsoul of Taia and recycled with Tenyi Spirit - Adhara. If you search for Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan, then you can use the Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna in your hand as fodder. If you search for Swordsoul Emergence, then you can use it to search for Archnemeses Protos.
Honestly... I don't have much to say

deck_name: Mayo with a side of Sleepy Girl
deck_description:
Hi, my name is Brady and I piloted this deck to a master 1 on master duel, after picking up the deck because the playstyle was fun and the art is cool. This is an attempt to port the deck over to the TCG format. I really like this deck, and in a format of snake-eyes fiendsmith that can play through up to 11 disruptions, a gameplan of breaking boards instead of disrupting them while they are being built feels much more viable. Because of this, my deck is built with only 3 handtraps (and an additional 6 in the sideboard) and instead uses those slots to help break boards and/or bait out disruption to set up your combo.

The theory behind this is that between Yosenju Oroshi Channeling, and Dream Tower of Princess Nemleria setting up a plus 1 for exactly the cards you need to OTK (that being 1 card scales set up or more large bodies to pendulum summon with those scales), or using Fire Formation - Tenki, Duelist Alliance, Luster Pendulum, the Dracoslayer, and Yosenju Sabu to go plus and set up your pendulum summon partially, all you need to do is use board breakers to deal with the relivant disruptions and punch a hole to resolve your important cards. This is also backed up by being an amazing Triple Tactics Thrust deck, as it finds either additional copies of board breakers, or your important starters.

After punching through opposing disruptions, winning is usually pretty easy. Your yosenju monsters ( Mayosenju Daibak Mayosenju Hitot Yosenju Kama 1 ) are often enough completely reset your opponent's board, especially with the help of kaijus, and are big enough to easily put together an OTK. Going first, however, sucks and so roughly half of the sideboard is dedicated to playing floodgates and the yosenju countertrap, to try and stun the opponent with relatively one sided effects. The idea is that your monsters are just bigger, and outside of skill drain, you can even bounce them back to your hand MP1, move to battlephase, then reset them MP2. 

Overall, the deck is supprisingly skill testing to play, and while being basically worse tenpai, it's not so much worse that with tight play and careful sideboarding, I think you could top at least a regional level event with a list like this.

deck_excerpt: Brick simulator, but more nefarious - Evil Eye, Phantom Knight, Burning Abyss
deck_description: Evil Eye, Phantom Knights and BA, what could possibly go wrong? (Rhetorical)
Monarch Test

So this deck is an edit to a deck I did back in February of this year. Look at that one for the main breakdown of the deck, because I am currently sick and can't be bothered to retype and re-evaluate all of the different tech I detailed in that description. Instead, I'm going to detail the information on what I cut and what I added as well as the why.

Cuts:
-1 D.D. Crow: The format isn't kind to this card currently. It's still a strong card and the attribute synergizes well, but top decks in MD just don't care about a single crow.
-1 Droll & Lock Bird: The attribute doesn't synergize, but it's still an incredibly strong floodgate of a card so it stays in.
-1 Vanquish Soul Jiaolong: Found it too bricky. Solid effect but too much effort and didn't come up as a necessity as often as I would think.
-1 Generaider Boss Quest: It's just not necessary when you have Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses.
-1 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy: Meta Shifted. New Charmer.
-1 Rock of the Vanquisher: You never needed 3, so I dropped one for S:P Little Knight 

Adds:
+1 Crossout Designator: I can't believe I was running this deck with so many targets and just said "NAH!"
+2 Called by the Grave: I shouldn't have to explain this one.
+2 Dark Ruler No More: I grabbed this because I wanted a board breaker. You can choose a different one you like, but this was MY choice.
+1 Hiita the Fire Charmer, Ablaze: Snake Eye dominance means this is the more relevant option over Dharc.
+1 S:P Little Knight: This requires no explanation. If you've seen this card in action, you know the why. If you haven't ever seen this card in play before and know a little bit of recent meta power cards, then your hint is "DPE".

Also yeah, you aren't mistaken, we went from 44 to 45. I won't start screaming until it goes to 46, but 45 still irritates even myself and if I could cut any of the engines down a little more, I would(Honestly, I probably could cut a Harr, Generaider Boss of Storms but then Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses is live less often so I keep him around at a full playset).

The deck's general strategy remains the same. You'll use the Generaider section primarily to assist your Vanquish Soul plays more than actually trying for huge power moves with the Generaider package I've installed into the deck. You're going for a more long game control style of play using the Vanquish Soul main package to bob and weave effects while outnumbering your opponent with grinding out card advantage and slowly whittling down the board. The Generaiders help by being only selected as the necessary attributes for the Vanquish Soul effects and don't feel horrible to run(Which is why we don't run Naglfar, Generaider Boss of Fire, Hela, Generaider Boss of Doom or Dovelgus, Generaider Boss of Iron). The only exception to the attribute rule was Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light because an easy search with a 2400 booty never hurt anyone, especially since he either baits an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring(If Loptr, Shadow of the Generaider Bosses didn't already do that if he was your summoning method for him), Droll & Lock Bird, Effect Veiler or Infinite Impermanence.
